Metadata.CommitMsg:
Fix: Correct brittle and environment-sensitive tests (#4)

This commit addresses several types of test failures caused by sensitivity to the underlying runtime environment (Node.js version, operating system). The test suite was failing due to hardcoded values and unreliable test strategies that differ across platforms.

The following changes were made to improve test robustness:

1.  **Robust Host Binding Test:** The tests in `mbTest/cli/hostTest.js` were unreliable because they used the machine's `hostname`, which can resolve to `localhost` on some systems, invalidating the test's premise. The fix implements an intelligent `before` hook that detects the network environment. It first tries to use the machine's hostname. If that resolves to `localhost`, it searches for a non-loopback IPv4 address to use instead. If no suitable host can be found, the tests are safely skipped with a console message.

2.  **IP Address Normalization:** Tests in `mbTest/cli/debugTest.js` were failing due to differences in how Node.js reports IP addresses (`127.0.0.1` vs `::1`). The test has been updated to normalize the IP address string before assertion, making it immune to this environmental difference.

3.  **Flexible JSON Error Assertion:** A test in `test/models/filesystemBackedImpostersRepositoryTest.js` checking for a JSON parsing error was failing. The root cause is that the exact error message string produced by the V8 JavaScript engine has changed in newer Node.js versions. The test has been made more robust by checking that the error `details` string starts with the expected text, rather than asserting an exact match.

These changes make the test suite significantly more robust and less prone to failures caused by minor environment variations.

Vulnerabilities.Title: cross-spawn: regular expression denial of service
Vulnerabilities.Description: Versions of the package cross-spawn before 6.0.6, from 7.0.0 and before 7.0.5 are vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) due to improper input sanitization. An attacker can increase the CPU usage and crash the program by crafting a very large and well crafted string.

Vulnerabilities.Title: Denial of Service in mem
Vulnerabilities.Description:
Versions of `mem` prior to 4.0.0 are vulnerable to Denial of Service (DoS).  The package fails to remove old values from the cache even after a value passes its `maxAge` property. This may allow attackers to exhaust the system's memory if they are able to abuse the application logging.


## Recommendation

Upgrade to version 4.0.0 or later.

npm-serialize-javascript: Cross-site Scripting (XSS) in serialize-javascript
Vulnerabilities.Description: A flaw was found in npm-serialize-javascript. The vulnerability occurs because the serialize-javascript module does not properly sanitize certain inputs, such as regex or other JavaScript object types, allowing an attacker to inject malicious code. This code could be executed when deserialized by a web browser, causing Cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks. This issue is critical in environments where serialized data is sent to web clients, potentially compromising the security of the website or web application using this package.

Vulnerabilities.Title: nodejs-yargs-parser: prototype pollution vulnerability
Vulnerabilities.Description: yargs-parser could be tricked into adding or modifying properties of Object.prototype using a "__proto__" payload.

Vulnerabilities.Title: ejs: server-side template injection in outputFunctionName
Vulnerabilities.Description: The ejs (aka Embedded JavaScript templates) package 3.1.6 for Node.js allows server-side template injection in settings[view options][outputFunctionName]. This is parsed as an internal option, and overwrites the outputFunctionName option with an arbitrary OS command (which is executed upon template compilation).
